      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying architecture and im a bit stuck on cantilevered geometry. can you explain how a cantilevered balcony manages to stay stable without any vertical supports at the outer edge? im specifically confused about how moment and torque play into the connection at the wall.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A cantilevered balcony remains stable through the careful design of the connection at the wall. Moment and torque are precisely calculated so that the forces are balanced. The cantilever acts like a lever, where the longer arm overpowering on the balcony applies a counter-moment to the wall through a carefully distributed load and reinforcements that prevent twisting, known as torque. The wall’s connection must resist bending, and the edge of the cantilever relies on rigidity to prevent deflection and eventual collapse. At the wall, the cantilevered balcony is often supported by a beam or rigidly connected element to provide the necessary counterbalance.",
