    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "One prominent example of a real-world failure related to moment calculation was the collapse of the Millennium Dome, also known as the \"Millennium Wheel,\" in London on October 30, 1999. The footbridge within the dome was supported by a cantilevered beam, and a design flaw led to a vortex of breath or airflow under the deck that dramatically collapsed the structure. This was an indirect failure pertaining to dynamic forces rather than static moments, but it demonstrates the critical importance of considering all potential forces, including ones that designers might not initially foresee.\n\n\nAnother example would be the partial collapse of the Copps Coliseum roof during an ice storm in 1991. The retractable roof dome typically operated using a combination of steel supports that were intended to hold the massive structure together. During the storm, issues with snowfall and ice accumulation, coupled with insufficient consideration of the dynamic loading due to snow and ice weight, led to the roof collapsing. The overwhelming dynamic loads combined with the static weight exceeded the capacities of the supporting elements constructed. This example is more of a failure involving a combination of static and dynamic loads not specifically concerning moments and torques, but it highlights the catastrophic consequences of failing to properly examine both aspects in a structure’s design and reinforcement",
      "source": "target",
